The value of CurSession.CallSystemStatus is a string indicating the current status of the executed system command. You can query its value in an OpenROAD application program by using the GetStatus method on the SessionObject object. An example of how to use it:
```
SessionObject session;
string s = session.GetStatus(CurSession.CallSystemStatus);
```

Starting a new OpenROAD application involves calling the operating system to execute the specified command. The call system statement can be used for this purpose. However, when you use call system statement in OpenROAD Actian 4GL, it is more efficient to use the call runimage statement because it creates a new process for executing the application code rather than starting another process that communicates with the existing process. Here are some examples:
* Starting a new OpenROAD application using call runimage statement:
call runimage "c:\actian\mynewapp";
* Starting a new OpenROAD application using call system statement in OpenROAD Actian 4GL:
call system "c:\actian\mynewapp\myapp.exe";

Starting a new OpenROAD application involves creating an object of type RunImage, specifying the name of an image file that contains the application code or data to be executed, specifying the application to use as the command processor (if required), and starting the application. This can be done using call runimage statement or by using the call system statement. The call runimage statement is generally more efficient than using the call system statement because it creates a new process for executing the application code. Here are some examples:
* Starting a new OpenROAD application using call runimage statement:
call runimage "c:\actian\mynewapp";
* Starting a new OpenROAD application using call system statement in OpenROAD Actian 4GL:
call system "c:\actian\mynewapp\myapp.exe";

You can use several techniques to share data between applications. You can write out files, put data in the database that can be read in by the other application or use shared memory (Windows only). Here is an example of writing a file that another application can read:
```
RunImage ri = new RunImage("myapp.runimg");
File file = new File("c:\data1.txt");
ri.PutText(file, "This is some data", true);
```
Here is an example using shared memory (Windows only):
```
RunImage ri = new RunImage("myapp.runimg");
byte[] data = new byte[20];
ri.GetSharedMem("sharedmem", 10, data, "readonly");
```
